│ stop({"edit_points": [[3363, 3384, "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe function          │
│ foldSelectOfBools transforms a boolean select into a logical and/or form and then defers to foldBooleanAndOr, which calls foldAndOrOfICmps with IsLogical=true. │
│ This is meant to ensure poison-safety (short-circuit semantics) when folding select-of-bools. However, foldAndOrOfICmps internally invokes a \"swapped\"        │
│ transform foldAndOrOfICmpEqConstantAndICmp(RHS, LHS, ..., IsLogical=false) that treats the logical operation as if it were a bitwise one and commutes operands. │
│ This can drop the original guard/short-circuit order and produce a result that uses only the RHS compare (e.g., icmp samesign), which can be poison even when   │
│ the original select would have short-circuited.\n\nIn the reproducer:\n  %cmp1 = icmp samesign eq i8 %x, -1\n  %cmp2 = icmp ne i8 %x, 0\n  %result = select i1  │
│ %cmp2, i1 %cmp1, i1 false\nInstCombine replaced the select with %cmp1, which is poison when %x == 0. The original select is well-defined (false) when %x == 0   │
│ because it does not evaluate the true arm. Alive2 shows the transform is incorrect: target more poisonous than source.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The first  │
│ transformation replaces the select directly with %cmp1 in foldSelectOfBools (InstCombineSelect.cpp:3368).\n- The decision comes from the foldBooleanAndOr path: │
│ it tries to fold select B ? C : false into B && C with IsLogical=true and then into just C due to an internal transform in foldAndOrOfICmps that swapped        │
│ operands and simplified the RHS-side compare and constant to just the RHS compare.\n- No samesign-drop occurred (final IR still shows \"icmp samesign eq\"), so │
│ poison remained.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- foldAndOrOfICmps, when IsLogical is true, still invokes a swapped direction transform using IsLogical=false:\n   │
│ if (Value *V = foldAndOrOfICmpEqConstantAndICmp(RHS, LHS, IsAnd, /*IsLogical=*/false, ...)) return V;\n- This breaks poison-safety: logical and/or is not       │
│ commutative w.r.t. poison because the first operand determines short-circuiting and whether a potentially poison RHS is used. Swapping can cause a previously   │
│ RHS poison value (like icmp samesign) to be evaluated first and then simplified to itself, eliminating the original guard and reintroducing poison. The ad-hoc  │
│ attempt to drop samesign on RHS does not always trigger (and even if it did, the reordering is still dangerous since other poison forms may exist).\n\n4.       │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp\n- Location: In InstCombinerImpl::foldAndOrOfICmps, around the second   │
│ call to foldAndOrOfICmpEqConstantAndICmp with swapped operands.\n- Change: Do not perform the swapped-direction transform when IsLogical is true. This          │
│ preserves the original short-circuit order and avoids turning a logical select form into an expression that evaluates the poison-producing comparison first or  │
│ drops the guard entirely.\n\nEdit:\nReplace the block:\n\n  if (Value *V = foldAndOrOfICmpEqConstantAndICmp(RHS, LHS, IsAnd,\n                                  │
│ /*IsLogical*/ false, Builder)) {\n    // If RHS is still used, we should drop samesign flag.\n    if (IsLogical && RHS->hasSameSign() && !RHS->use_empty()) {\n │
│ RHS->setSameSign(false);\n      addToWorklist(RHS);\n    }\n    return V;\n  }\n\nwith:\n\n  if (!IsLogical)\n    if (Value *V =                                │
│ foldAndOrOfICmpEqConstantAndICmp(RHS, LHS, IsAnd,\n                                                    /*IsLogical*/ false, Builder))\n      return             │
│ V;\n\nRationale:\n- When IsLogical is true (folding a select-of-bools), we must preserve short-circuit semantics and must not commute operands or introduce     │
│ bitwise operations that could change which side is evaluated first. Skipping the swapped-direction transform in the logical context prevents the observed       │
│ miscompile.\n- We also remove the special-case samesign drop in that block, as it would no longer execute in the logical context and is unnecessary in the      │
│ preserved bitwise-only path.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug stems from treating logical (select) boolean folding as bitwise in a swapped direction, which can       │
│ reorder operands and eliminate the guard that protected against poison (e.g., icmp samesign). By disabling the swapped-direction transform when IsLogical is    │
│ true, we prevent reordering and ensure that transforms remain poison-safe. The select will no longer be incorrectly replaced by the poison-producing compare,   │
│ fixing the Alive2 failure and maintaining correctness.\n"})                                                                                                     │
